This is problem with random quizzes, e-mail, very little context and quite a
few bright minds!

Depending on what the resource truly is, then 200 (or 400) take on different
meaning.  If the date is the actual resource, then yes, 200 (I believe)
would indicate that the resource (date) does exist (and is a leap year).
This is where GET is probably not needed and HEAD could be used solely.

However, if the resource in question is &quot;testing that date is a leap year&quot;,
then 200 takes on a very different meaning as it communicates whether the
resource that tests for leap years is/was available.  The response would
still have to be inspected.

My $0.02.

Ebenezer

